So let's start with ... let's start with RNNs and then go from there. So kind of the last two chapters, chapter 13 on RNN basics, and chapter 14 on training rnn's for nlp.

So we have sequential data where ordering matters, if we use that in a fully connected feed forward NNs this data is lost, we just feed one training after another. Hence, we might benefit from a new architecture that might use the ordering of data as information in making predictions.

Here RNNs come. Think same NN, but you also feed the output of the layer/neuron from the past training instance. All else works practically just like a normal NN. We also have weights for activations of the same layer for the past training instance, so we just as well do backprop on them. 
One thing to understand how it works, is that in a deep layered RNN the neuron gets both the activation vector of its input layer, and the activation vector of its own layer for the past training instance.

There are different types of RNNs:
    - seq2seq -- time series prediction
    - seq2vec -- sentiment analysis
    - vec2seq -- image caption
    - encoder-decoder: seq2vec-vec2seq, NMT

depending on the type of RNN loss function would be a bit different, like in seq2vec we'll ignore all but last output (hidden state)

There are some of the issues with RNNs, like gradient explosion, and (🟡 took a bit of time to recall) very short term memory!
Think of gradient explosion. Basically if the activation output of one layer is slightly increased, then we keep on passing it through to future training instances, so it easily can balloon. What to do? Saturating activation functions like sigmoids, instead of non-saturating ones like ReLU. You also need good weight initialization, gradient clipping and right learning rate.

Now think short-term memory. Basically we have info about the past training instance, so image NLP case, you read the sentence and by the time you get to its end you forgot how it started. This is because network has to pass start of sentence info all throughout several training instances iterations. This is hard! So for the things that matter, like NLP RNNs are practically unusable.

To fix that we again can try a new architecture! An improvement on RNNs for fixing short term memory is LSTM and GRU. Basically the idea is that network can learn also what information to save for future recall, and then retrieve it when needed. 

To explain that let's do LSTM. It stands for long short term memory, which pretty much explains the main idea. Instead of just passing by past training instance info, we also have long-term memory stream, where network learns what information to keep, and when to retrieve it. Instead of neurons we call them cells, and cells have gates, which help with deciding what info to keep and what to skip for long-term stream. I don't know more than that level of detail. So cells produce two streams of outputs, short-term memory h_t, and long-term memory c_t. which is again passed to all the neurons etc. So now we have 3 things that neurons get, info from their input layer, short-term info from their own layer activation from past training instance, and lastly long-term info (🟡 but from where that long-term memory comes from? i guess past training instance activations of the same layer.)

Now that's LSTM and they're doing better for long-sequence processing than RNNs. We could simplify their architecture and get GRUs that have again one stream h_t that combines both short and long-term memory. That's kind of the main thing I want to know, I think that's the right level of abstraction.

