So, RNNs for NLP.

First, NLP is usually long-sequence processing so we use LSTMs and GRU, and practically always GRU. Working with text means we need to do quite some preprocessing of it for NN to do useful things with it, giving its architecture and biases. 

Also depends on the task we're doing with that text. Let's talk text generation, not sentiment analysis.

(🟡 also didn't mention similar batch size with padding tokens, and how we trim them afterwards...)

First we have our block of text, for NN to work with it and give us something out we need to break it down into __workable chunks__. There are different ways of doing it, one way is to use characters, this works for short-text, but harder for long-sequences. Ideally, we want to give network the biggest workable chunk of text, so it can do longer-sequence understanding and generation of text. For that we can use tokens, which are like popular subwords into which text can be broken. That's the right level of abstraction for nn to operate with text. So, let's talk how you choose the right tokens.

There are several algorithms, usually you use pretrained, and even lowest layers of some other large language model (reusing things is a very common pattern in DL to save oneself time, don't reinvent bike from scratch). Those are: BPE, unigram, wordpiece.

Say we use pretrained, or just trained on our own those tokens. What we have now is a dictionary with all those tokens and say their corresponding ids. 

Network obviously needs numbers to work with, so we could use those ids. But nothing good would come out of that because network has very strong bias for close numbers meaning similar things. So instead of id's which is like 10k-50k numbers, we can represent them as dense vectors, i.e. embedding that has like 300 dimensions.

So each token gets a vector, first randomly, and then adjacent to training model weights, we train those vectors to represent similar tokens close to each other. In fact by the end we can even do some math with words, like king-men+women=queen! (which is still crazy even though that's not my first time explaining it.)

But why train it ourselves when we can just takes someones pretrained version! Say, also with their tokens, and their first few model layers which we first freeze not to damage them with super high gradients at the start of the training.

And the tokens is like a dictionary with which network operates, so it outputs basically a classification of a huge, like 10k dictionary, so we train it with cross entropy.

Cool, we have processed our text into smallest biggest workable chunks, i.e. tokens, instead of id's we represent them as vectors, we put them as dense representation, and train it so that similar vectors are closeby and we can do kind of math with language. We maybe also reused first layers of some other language model. Very good start! 

